<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53f3682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:17.</label.designator><headtext>Search and seizure—Schools</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>School searches present a variation of the “private person” <page no="134"/>problem. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1974129392" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe59ae27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Young v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30c8f107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] an assistant principal of a public high school directed the defendant, a 17-year-old student, to empty his pockets in the principal&apos;s office. <eos/><bos/>The defendant was charged and convicted for possessing less than an ounce of marijuana. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that the school official was a government officer subject to the restraints of the Fourth Amendment and that the evidence should have been suppressed. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court reversed[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30c8f117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] holding that the assistant high school principal was not a “public officer” or “law enforcement officer” and the “reasonable suspicion” standard was sufficient for the search.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic30c8f127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Subsequently, the Court of Appeals followed <ital>Young</ital> in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1976115778" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe796b27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>State v. Lamb</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30cb6207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] where it upheld the “reasonable suspicion” standard in a dormitory supervisor&apos;s search of a dormitory room in which marijuana plants were growing.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, if a law enforcement officer (even one working an additional job as a security guard) assists school personnel in the search, the search is held to the higher probable cause standard.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic30cb6217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Iffe91d547fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>New Jersey v. T.L.O.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30cb6227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] the United States Supreme Court reiterated that the Fourth Amendment applies to searches conducted by public school officials and the legality the search of a student depends on its reasonableness under all the circumstances.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Court of Appeals discussed <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Iffea55d47fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>T.L.O.</ital></cite.query> in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="2000395500" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffea55d77fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Patman v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30cb6237fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] where it explained that <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“a student&apos;s interest in privacy must be balanced against <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>‘the substantial interest of teachers and administrators in maintaining discipline in the classroom and on school grounds.’<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30cdd307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] Accordingly, the Fourth Amendment permits school officials to search students based upon circumstances which do not rise to the level of probable cause, and <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[i]n Georgia, school officials may search subject only to the most minimal restraints necessary to insure that students are not <page no="135"/>whimsically stripped of personal privacy and subjected to petty tyranny.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic30cdd317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic30c8f107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1974129392" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe5e9027fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Young v. State, 132 Ga. App. 790, 209 S.E.2d 96 (1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30c8f117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1975131402" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe65e327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Young, 234 Ga. 488, 216 S.E.2d 586 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30c8f127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1975131402" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe6d3627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Young, 234 Ga. 488, 216 S.E.2d 586 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cb6207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1976115778" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe7bdc27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Lamb, 137 Ga. App. 437, 224 S.E.2d 51 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cb6217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1978132486" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffe881107fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Trippe, 146 Ga. App. 210, 246 S.E.2d 122 (1978)</cite.query>, the Georgia Court of Appeals affirmed the trial court&apos;s motion to suppress on the ground that a school security officer, who was also a special deputy sheriff, was acting as a law enforcement officer as he assisted school personnel in the dormitory search.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cb6227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Iffe944647fbf11ea988285db8533e975">New Jersey v. T.L.O., 469 U.S. 325, 105 S. Ct. 733, 83 L. Ed. 2d 720, 21 Ed. Law Rep. 1122 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cb6237fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="2000395500" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffeaa3f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Patman v. State, 244 Ga. App. 833, 537 S.E.2d 118 (2000)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cdd307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="2000395500" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffeb19227fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Patman v. State, 244 Ga. App. 833, 834, 537 S.E.2d 118 (2000)</cite.query> (quoting <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Iffeb19277fbf11ea988285db8533e975">New Jersey v. T.L.O., 469 U.S. 325, 339, 105 S. Ct. 733, 83 L. Ed. 2d 720, 21 Ed. Law Rep. 1122 (1985)</cite.query>).<eos/><page no="135"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic30cdd317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="2000395500" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffebb5627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Patman v. State, 244 Ga. App. 833, 834, 537 S.E.2d 118 (2000)</cite.query> (quoting <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1975131402" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iffebb5657fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Young, 234 Ga. 488, 497, 216 S.E.2d 586 (1975)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 4:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
